There is no single AWS CLI command that auto-creates WAF the same way the CloudFront console “one-click protection” does. That one-click flow is a console feature that creates a WAF Web ACL, adds recommended protections, and attaches it to the distribution. 

CLI equivalent = create WAF first, then create CloudFront distribution with that WAF ARN attached.

1. Create WAF rules file

Create waf-rules.json:

[
  {
    "Name": "AWS-AWSManagedRulesCommonRuleSet",
    "Priority": 0,
    "Statement": {
      "ManagedRuleGroupStatement": {
        "VendorName": "AWS",
        "Name": "AWSManagedRulesCommonRuleSet"
      }
    },
    "OverrideAction": {
      "Count": {}
    },
    "VisibilityConfig": {
      "SampledRequestsEnabled": true,
      "CloudWatchMetricsEnabled": true,
      "MetricName": "AWSManagedRulesCommonRuleSet"
    }
  },
  {
    "Name": "AWS-AWSManagedRulesAmazonIpReputationList",
    "Priority": 1,
    "Statement": {
      "ManagedRuleGroupStatement": {
        "VendorName": "AWS",
        "Name": "AWSManagedRulesAmazonIpReputationList"
      }
    },
    "OverrideAction": {
      "Count": {}
    },
    "VisibilityConfig": {
      "SampledRequestsEnabled": true,
      "CloudWatchMetricsEnabled": true,
      "MetricName": "AWSManagedRulesAmazonIpReputationList"
    }
  }
]

I used Count mode so production traffic is not blocked immediately. Later, change "Count": {} to "None": {} after checking WAF logs.

2. Create WAF Web ACL for CloudFront

WEB_ACL_ARN=$(aws wafv2 create-web-acl \
  --profile prod \
  --region us-east-1 \
  --name prod-cloudfront-waf \
  --scope CLOUDFRONT \
  --default-action '{"Allow":{}}' \
  --visibility-config '{"SampledRequestsEnabled":true,"CloudWatchMetricsEnabled":true,"MetricName":"prod-cloudfront-waf"}' \
  --rules file://waf-rules.json \
  --query 'Summary.ARN' \
  --output text)

echo "$WEB_ACL_ARN"

For CloudFront WAF, the scope must be CLOUDFRONT, and AWS requires the WAF API call to use us-east-1. 

3. Create CloudFront distribution config with WAF attached

Create distribution-config.json:

cat > distribution-config.json <<EOF
{
  "CallerReference": "prod-$(date +%s)",
  "Comment": "Production CloudFront distribution with WAF",
  "Enabled": true,
  "Aliases": {
    "Quantity": 0
  },
  "Origins": {
    "Quantity": 1,
    "Items": [
      {
        "Id": "app-origin",
        "DomainName": "REPLACE_WITH_ORIGIN_DOMAIN",
        "CustomOriginConfig": {
          "HTTPPort": 80,
          "HTTPSPort": 443,
          "OriginProtocolPolicy": "https-only",
          "OriginSslProtocols": {
            "Quantity": 1,
            "Items": ["TLSv1.2"]
          },
          "OriginReadTimeout": 30,
          "OriginKeepaliveTimeout": 5
        }
      }
    ]
  },
  "DefaultCacheBehavior": {
    "TargetOriginId": "app-origin",
    "ViewerProtocolPolicy": "redirect-to-https",
    "AllowedMethods": {
      "Quantity": 2,
      "Items": ["GET", "HEAD"],
      "CachedMethods": {
        "Quantity": 2,
        "Items": ["GET", "HEAD"]
      }
    },
    "Compress": true,
    "CachePolicyId": "658327ea-f89d-4fab-a63d-7e88639e58f6"
  },
  "PriceClass": "PriceClass_All",
  "ViewerCertificate": {
    "CloudFrontDefaultCertificate": true
  },
  "Restrictions": {
    "GeoRestriction": {
      "RestrictionType": "none",
      "Quantity": 0
    }
  },
  "WebACLId": "$WEB_ACL_ARN"
}
EOF

For AWS WAF v2, CloudFront expects the Web ACL ARN in the distribution config’s WebACLId field. 

4. Create the distribution

aws cloudfront create-distribution \
  --profile prod \
  --distribution-config file://distribution-config.json

Replace REPLACE_WITH_ORIGIN_DOMAIN with your real origin, for example:

my-prod-alb-123456.ap-northeast-1.elb.amazonaws.com

or your API/custom origin domain.

In your case, since you’re copying from staging, compare origins, behaviors, cache policies, origin request policies, and WAF rules carefully; a WAF block can make /api/* look broken before the request even reaches the origin. 